- content_for(:title, 'Conversion Chart')
%p
  The MBTI theory defines you as what you
  %em prefer
  most (your dominant
  =(link_to "function-attitude", "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jungian_cognitive_functions", class: "external") + ")"
  and adds what you prefer second as an auxiliary function-attitude (constrained by the MBTI theory to only two choices based on your first choice). Tertiary and Inferior function-attitudes are also constrained by the theory (based on your first two choices). Thus the MBTI has sixteen types (eight times two).
%p
  The BipolarType theory defines your type based not on what you prefer, but on what you are most
  %em balanced
  in. But BipolarType does not constrain realms except in that they must be unique. Thus BipolarType has twenty-four types (four factorial).
%p
  Of the twenty-four BipolarTypes, only four correspond to MBTI types. Even if you have determined your
  =link_to "best-fit MBTI type", "https://www.myersbriggs.org/unique-features-of-myers-briggs/best-fit-type/", class: "external"
  it probably does
  %em not
  determine your BipolarType. However, you can still try starting with the GetStrength realm of that type as thatâ€™s the first question on the
  =link_to "Your BipolarType", answer_path(Answer.first_path)
  page.
